observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed that the following courses of actions be observed:
The Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant reconcile their records on the above noted variance;
Management consider complying with the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
The Inventory Committee initiate the disposal of all unserviceable PPEs;
Pending disposal, the Municipal Accountant recognize additional impairment loss using the estimated recoverable service amount of each unserviceable property;
The Inventory Committee perform complete inventory-taking and ensure that all accountable persons present the items under their custody and put/ update the property tags at the same time; and
The Inventory Committee use the prescribed RPCPPE format and reflect the actual property items counted during the physical inventory.

We recommended and Management agreed that the following courses of actions be observed:
The Inventory Committee conduct a physical count of all the supplies and semi-expendable properties at least twice a year;
The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the inventory reports to the Audit Team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year in accordance with the provisions of the above-mentioned manual;
The Municipal Treasurer maintain SCs and prepare the SSMI and RSPI that shall be used by Municipal Accountant in the preparation of JEV to record the expenditures and in recognizing the semi-expendable property issued; and
The Municipal Accountant maintain SLCs and ensure that controls over Inventory accounts were implemented.

We recommended that the Municipal Account;
Make the necessary adjustments using the proposed adjusting journal entries presented in Appendix G; and
Reclassify to Due to LGUs the ₱40,000.00 recorded as other payables to the contractor for the Riprapping at Sitio Danikop, Basak pending its return to the Source Agency.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Send confirmation letters to the identified source agencies to verify the existence of these payables in their respective books or records;
Provide the Office of the President, in coordination with the Acting Municipal Treasurer, the soonest with references they needed for them to check in their records the transferred ₱1,000,000.00 from the President’s Social Fund;
Confer with the Office of the Provincial Accountant of the Province of Cebu to account for the outstanding receivables that needs to be liquidated; and
In relation to the immediately preceding recommendation, reclassify the excess financial assistance not included therefrom to Prior Period Adjustment (Miscellaneous Income) and coordinate with the Acting Municipal Treasurer to include these as a new funding source subject to budgetary laws and regulations.

The Municipal Mayor instruct the concerned officials to:

exert effort in locating the PPEs that were not found during the physical count, otherwise, make the necessary adjusting entries in the books to reflect the losses and held the accountable officers liable for the losses discovered;

provide property numbers for each PPE items for easy identification and monitoring;

dispose unserviceable properties in accordance with applicable rules and regulations, otherwise, recognize impairment loss to reflect the true carrying value of the assets;

exert effort to account the composition of the bulk balances carried over from the previous years;

make the necessary adjusting entries to derecognize the assets already disposed from the books of accounts; and

submit the lapsing schedules in support of the total depreciation expenses recognized for CY 2020.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the concerned officials to:
exert effort in locating the PPEs that were not found during the physical count, otherwise, make the necessary adjusting entries in the books to reflect the losses and held the accountable officers liable for the losses discovered;
provide property numbers for each PPE items for easy identification and monitoring;
dispose unserviceable properties in accordance with applicable rules and regulations, otherwise, recognize impairment loss to reflect the true carrying value of the assets;
exert effort to account the composition of the bulk balances carried over from the previous years;
make the necessary adjusting entries to derecognize the assets already disposed from the books of accounts; and
submit the lapsing schedules in support of the total depreciation expenses recognized for CY 2020.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
1. Direct the Municipal Engineering Office to submit disbursement vouchers together with copies of Certificate of Completion/ Statement of Work Accomplished (SWA) on completed projects to the Municipal Accountant for processing and proper recording in the books of accounts;
2. Advise the Municipal Accountant to reclassify completed projects into the appropriate asset account based on the submitted documents by the Municipal Engineering Office to its related PPE, and;
3. Recognize the related depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation for the said projects from the time they were available for use.

We recommended Management to:
a. Direct the Accounting Office and General Services Office to determine the difference of their records and make necessary adjustments if any, and;
b. Require the Inventory Committee to convene and strategize the conduct of physical count of all Properties Plant and Equipment of the municipality to present a more realistic report.

We recommended management to:
a. Strictly enforce the period of liquidation as prescribed above and require the immediate refund/return of any excess amount thereof;
b. Demand the immediate settlement of the unliquidated cash advances amounting to P127,650.33 from persons concerned;
c. Direct the offices concerned to develop strategies to expedite collections and to enforce loan payment per provisions of the MOA/Contract.
d. If the circumstances warrant, request for write-off for receivables where the settlement/collectability can no longer be ascertained as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended that Management: 

•	submit immediately the lacking documents and liquidation reports from the barangays;

•	instruct the Accountant to make the necessary adjustments to correct the balances of the relevant accounts;

•	henceforth, ensure that financial assistance to barangays be supported with the necessary documents to ensure the diligent and judicious utilization of public funds.

We recommended that Management:
submit immediately the lacking documents and liquidation reports from the barangays;
instruct the Accountant to make the necessary adjustments to correct the balances of the relevant accounts;
henceforth, ensure that financial assistance to barangays be supported with the necessary documents to ensure the diligent and judicious utilization of public funds.

We recommended management to:
Observe the additional information required by PPSAS that is not shown on the face of the financial statements but relevant to an understanding;
Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjustment on the variances noted to correct the reported balances of the affected accounts in the Financial Statements.

We recommended management the following:
Carefully plan and organize the project management plan and ensure that the program of works and other related plans and designs were already done and properly reviewed and approved to carry out the project upon its implementation effectively;
Fast track the implementation of this project and require the Engineering and Operations & Maintenance sections key personnel to monitor the project implementation closely;
Act with dispatch in resolving the existing issue/problems that are currently hampering/delaying the implementation of projects;
Make sure that that the timeline set for every program/project is realistic and is strictly followed.

We recommended the Municipal Treasurer to:
Coordinate with the Municipal Assessor’s Office and devise a comprehensive strategy primarily focused on the collection of delinquent property taxes to reduce the outstanding amount of delinquencies substantially;
Request sufficient funding for plantilla position and for other needs of the office to facilitate effective property tax collection, monitoring, and assessment;
Coordinate with the Municipal Assessor and Treasurer of the concerned municipalities with Boundary Conflict and Double Declaration to settle the duplication of assessment of RPUs and avoid incurrence of additional delinquent accounts;
Identify the owners of properties under CARP and discuss with them the status of their properties and the settlement of their accountabilities.
Deputized the Barangay Treasurers, especially in remote barangays, to be collecting agents in accordance with Section 247 of RA No. 7160 to assist in the collection and monitoring of RPT accounts.
Reconcile the records with the Municipal Assessor’s Office and update the software, if necessary.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
The Accounting Unit to prepare the cash advance vouchers  instead of the Treasury Unit;
The Municipal Accountant to strictly implement COA Circular No. 97-002  by ensuring that  cash advances  for payroll should be supported by payroll or list of payees with their net payments;
c)	The Municipal Accountant should ensure that all mathematical computation, footing and cross footing in the payroll are accurate.

We recommended the following courses of action:

Intensify collection through sending follow-up letters/notices of delinquent stall/rentals to remind them of their obligations;

Cause the immediate Cancellation of the business permit or licenses in order not to accumulate the interest and surcharges;

For those lessees who are no longer in business confiscate the stall/lot to award to another interested one; and 

Direct also the LEEDMO to inspect/ follow-up the stall space occupants’ delinquencies to improve the revenue generation of the Municipality.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor require:
The Accounting Unit to prepare the cash advance vouchers  instead of the Treasury Unit;
The Municipal Accountant to strictly implement COA Circular No. 97-002  by ensuring that  cash advances  for payroll should be supported by payroll or list of payees with their net payments;
The Municipal Accountant should ensure that all mathematical computation, footing and cross footing in the payroll are accurate.
